@NODE What "What is it?"

Blitz-Download is a 2 program package which forms part of the M-Tag package.
It can, however, be used without the M-Tag package just as easily.

Blitz-Download performs 2 functions:

       o Allows your users to download the descriptions to the files in
         their tag list.

       o Copies files from specified @{"units" link config} to the HD.

@ENDNODE
@NODE running "How to run it"

Blitz-Download takes 1 optional parameter. Call Blitz-Download thus:

       Blitz-Download [COPYCD]

If you are not using the M-Tag package, you will need to use a menu script
to use when your users choose to download. An example menu script might be:

EXE Blitz-Download COPYCD
BUILTIN File_Download

By using the COPYCD option, you will turn on Blitz-Download's CD copying
function. This function will copy files which exist on a configured @{"unit" link config}.

When using the COPYCD option, you will also need to use a @{"config file" link config}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE CDC "CD-Clean"

This program is used to tidy-up the HD which holds the files copied from CD.
It will scan the directory and delete all files/directories which are no
longer needed.

It takes one optional parameter. This paramter is used to get a device's
unit number. DO NOT pass a parameter when you wish to clean the hard drive,
as it will not do anything.

It is adviseable to run this a few times a day from a cron event.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Config "Configuring Blitz-Download"

If using the COPYCD option, you will need to use a config file. The config
file is called 'DLGConfig:Misc/Blitz-Download.cfg'. It is a simple ASCII
file, and takes the following form:

Line 1: The path where you want to put the files. MUST have a trailing slash
        or colon.

              Eg: DH4:CD_Copy/

Line 2: List of unit's that require copying. The unit number as returned by
        the DOS call Info(). This is usually the SCSI ID number for the
        drive. Sepaerate unit numbers by a comma ONLY. For a CD-Stacker on
        SCSI ID 5, the following would be good to use:

              5,15,25,35,45,55

        You can get the unit number of a device by using the following:

              CDC <device_name>

Line 3: Amount of memory to use for copy buffer, in bytes.
Line 4: Amount of free space which must be available on the destination
        drive. If less than 10000, this value is multiplied by 1024.

@ENDNODE
